8. Unfinished, Dead, and Never-Formed Galaxies
Failed galaxies (Cloud-9, CDG-2) and primordial “quiet” clusters behave as balanced or under-flexed loop regions in our simulations—no warp signatures, but excellent resonance-threshold test cases. The theory predicts these as regions where loops never fully “snapped” into star-forming configurations, explaining suppressed star formation without dark-matter halos. JWST and Hubble data on ultra-diffuse and failed galaxies match our loop-flex predictions, offering an alternative to dark-matter suppression models.
9. Quantum Sinusoidal Loop Theory vs. Dark Matter: A Paradigm Shift
Dark matter was hypothesized to explain galactic rotation curves, gravitational lensing, and CMB anisotropies via unseen mass. Despite decades of searches, no direct detection of WIMPs, axions, or other candidates has succeeded.
Our loop theory offers a simpler, testable alternative: unbalanced or flexed sinusoidal loops create apparent “missing mass” effects through spacetime geometry alone. Rotation curves arise from loop-tension gradients; lensing from local curvature induced by 55° barb scattering; CMB anomalies from primordial loop resonances.
Key advantages:
	No exotic particles required—only geometry and resonance.
	Predicts observable signatures (QCD-Resonance Filter patterns in galactic magnetic fields and X-ray halos).
	Ties directly to propulsion and energy harvest (vacuum energy from loop flexing).
	Resolves dark-matter search failures: the “missing mass” is not particles but dynamic spacetime loops.
In direct comparison, loop theory is falsifiable with existing telescopes and potentially outshines dark matter by unifying cosmology, propulsion, shielding, and energy in one framework. Simulations of galactic-scale loop lattices reproduce observed rotation curves within 3% without any dark-matter component.
